    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "b87dee17-4242-4d83-9f36-63aae1204d93",
      "key": "7ffdb4cf-8224-4994-bd2b-7176f62b9d01",
      "values": [
        {
          "alias": "content",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": {
            "blocks": {
              "contentData": [],
              "settingsData": [],
              "expose": [],
              "Layout": {}
            },
            "markup": "\u003Cp\u003EMicrosoft Narrator is a piece of software called a screen reader. A screen reader does exactly what the name suggests: it reads out what is on the screen using synthesized speech. On Windows, there are three pieces of screen reader software that blind or low vision users will typically use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EJob Access With Speech (JAWS) from Freedom Scientific.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-Visual Desktop Access (NVDA) a free, open-source screen reader from NVAccess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMicrosoft Narrator from Microsoft, built into the Windows operating system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis guide is about Narrator. Though Narrator is the least used out of the three, it is the easiest to reach and useful for quick testing. For more comprehensive testing, NVDA is recommended to be used, as more people use it over Narrator and it is very similar to JAWS.\u003C/p\u003E"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "a8790ec0-2c08-4153-8546-9c5ef4763691",
      "key": "9bc86845-1c81-407a-ab83-d819fa368eb4",
      "values": [
        {
          "alias": "headerText",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": "How to enable Narrator"
        },
        {
          "alias": "headerTextColor",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": {
            "label": "black",
            "value": "#000000"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "b87dee17-4242-4d83-9f36-63aae1204d93",
      "key": "a86a2176-26ab-49c7-894f-781e139cfb35",
      "values": [
        {
          "alias": "content",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": {
            "blocks": {
              "contentData": [],
              "settingsData": [],
              "expose": [],
              "Layout": {}
            },
            "markup": "\u003Cp\u003EThere are two ways to enable Narrator:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOpen the Start menu, type \u201CNarrator\u201D, and hit \u0022Enter\u0022\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPress the keyboard combination Windows key\u002B Control\u002B Enter \u2013 This will also turn it off if it\u2019s already on.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBoth methods are equally valid, but the keyboard shortcut is faster.\u003C/p\u003E"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "a8790ec0-2c08-4153-8546-9c5ef4763691",
      "key": "13b29610-be0d-4764-8b08-1244b3eb58e7",
      "values": [
        {
          "alias": "headerText",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": "The Narrator key"
        },
        {
          "alias": "headerTextColor",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": {
            "label": "black",
            "value": "#000000"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "b87dee17-4242-4d83-9f36-63aae1204d93",
      "key": "7c66f1ef-786a-442e-9c58-22cd413d5b70",
      "values": [
        {
          "alias": "content",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": {
            "blocks": {
              "contentData": [],
              "settingsData": [],
              "expose": [],
              "Layout": {}
            },
            "markup": "\u003Cp\u003EFor some keyboard commands in Narrator, you have to press what is called the Narrator Key. By default, you can use the Insert or Caps Lock keys, but you can change it in the Narrator settings.\u003C/p\u003E"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "a8790ec0-2c08-4153-8546-9c5ef4763691",
      "key": "4c28f2b6-3d14-4f4a-a75e-3a5bef85bdaf",
      "values": [
        {
          "alias": "headerText",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": "Screen Curtain"
        },
        {
          "alias": "headerTextColor",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": {
            "label": "black",
            "value": "#000000"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "b87dee17-4242-4d83-9f36-63aae1204d93",
      "key": "75c85617-5926-4681-9434-76d7bff440bf",
      "values": [
        {
          "alias": "content",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": {
            "blocks": {
              "contentData": [],
              "settingsData": [],
              "expose": [],
              "Layout": {}
            },
            "markup": "\u003Cp\u003ENarrator, like other screen readers, has a useful feature that can be used for testing called screen curtain. The screen curtain blacks out your entire screen without the need to turn off your monitor. Unlike NVDA, Narrator has a keyboard shortcut to enable and disable this feature. To toggle the screen curtain, you press the Narrator key\u002BControl\u002BC. The narrator will announce when the screen curtain is on and when it\u2019s off.\u003C/p\u003E"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
